🔥 Excellent. Now you’re thinking at the right level.

You’re right — both mock and spy check whether a method was called.

So what’s the real difference?

It’s not what they check.

It’s when and how they set the expectation.

Let’s break it cleanly.

✅ Both Mock and Spy Check Method Calls

Both of these verify:

“Was send_email called?”

Mock
expect(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)

PaymentProcessor.new.call(user)
Spy
allow(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)

PaymentProcessor.new.call(user)

expect(NotificationService).to have_received(:send_email)

Both fail if the method wasn’t called.

So yes — they are checking the same thing.

🔥 The REAL Difference
1️⃣ Mock → Expectation Before Execution

You declare:

“This MUST be called.”

Then you run the code.

RSpec is already waiting for that call.

This is called pre-execution expectation.

2️⃣ Spy → Verify After Execution

You allow the method to be tracked.

Then after execution you ask:

“Did it get called?”

This is called post-execution verification.

🧠 Mental Model

Mock =
📢 “I demand this happens.”

Spy =
🕵️ “Let’s see what happened.”

⚡ Why Spy Is Often Preferred

Spy follows the clean testing structure:

Arrange
Act
Assert

Example:

# Arrange
allow(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)

# Act
PaymentProcessor.new.call(user)

# Assert
expect(NotificationService).to have_received(:send_email)

That reads naturally.

Mocks mix Arrange + Assert together.

🚨 Important Behavioral Difference

With a mock:

expect(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)

If the method is never called → test fails automatically at end.

With spy:

If you forget this line:

expect(NotificationService).to have_received(:send_email)

The test will PASS.

Because allow alone does not assert anything.

This is a very important difference.

🎯 Interview-Level Answer

If interviewer asks:

“What’s the difference between mock and spy if both check method calls?”

You say:

Both verify that a method was called, but mocks set the expectation before execution using expect(...).to receive, while spies verify after execution using have_received. Spies follow Arrange–Act–Assert style and are generally cleaner.

